title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 1892 in 218 Bee – EXCEPTIONALLY RARE!
postcontent: This particular Model 92 (serial #985713) is in good condition with a very good bore. The receiver is typically showing much less finish than the barrel. The sight hood was removed from the two barrel pics but is on the gun. The fore stock is not quite beaver tailed, but a little thicker than a typical 1892 forearm. The butt stock is a typical Model 53 style. It is just over 3000 serials later than the one pictured in the Madis book, but the same year of production. The .218 Bee caliber was not formally offered until the advent of the Model 65 in 1933. There were reportedly some Models 53 special ordered in .218 Bee (standard caliber was .25-20), and, as evidenced by this gun, a very few Models of 1892 as well.

title: For Sale:  Brand New Fully LOADED Midlength 18" AR-15 1:9 Keymod
postcontent: Up for grabs is a brand new AR-15 in 556/223 with tons of upgrades and add-ons to make this one smooth-shooting, sharp-looking, rifle. This was my personal baby; I planned to use it as my 'yote gun. I have some additional extras you can add for a nominal cost of you want to make this a COMPLETELY upgraded rifle. Radical Firearms lower assembly made in Texas with a LUTH-AR skeleton fixed stock and an Ergo overmolded grip--one of THE MOST comfortable on the market, in my opinion. Hardened Arms upper with an 18" mid-length HBAR 1:9 twist melonited barrel.I have multiple Radical Firearms and Hardened Arms rifles (556, 300 Blackout, 6.5 Grendel) and all of them are sub-MOA tack drivers. On the upper I swapped the 10" quad rail for a 15" USA-made Guntec ultraslim, lightweight keymod handguard. 18" barrel is perfect for varmints, targets, or whatever you want to do. 1:9 twist with the longer barrel provides enough twist and barrel to run everything from 40-77gr bullets accurately. HBAR configuration with the lightweight handguard gives the perfect balance for shooting--great harmonics and stability of a heavier barrel for the best accuracy, but light enough to be comfortable to carry out in the field. Comes a standard A2 birdcage flash hider (melonited with chatter on it, or phosphate coated without chatter marls)I replaced the gritty, milspec trigger with a brand new Palmetto State Armory Nickel Boron fire control group with reduced weight spring. Trigger is nice and smooth with just a hint of creep, then breaks cleanly amd reliably at 4.5#. I've shot much pricier single stage triggers that didn't feel nearly as nice. I initially planned to upgrade to a $150-200 single stage, but once I finished the trigger job on this, I saw no need. The extra money wouldn't buy me anything better.I also added a melonited extended front take-down pin. Makes disassembly much easier. Additionally, I replaced the trigger pins with anti-walk pins to keep them in there no matter what angle you shoot from.Lower has a few subtle red highlights--Seekins oversize trigger guard and extended mag release button, and a Strike Industries red charging handle with extended handle (for your convenience when you add your own optic). Just enough to be different, without being overbearing bling.I love the LUTH-AR stock and have another one on my Grendel. You can use as is (I've got some cheek/comb risers I can throw in if you want them--just ask), OR for about $60, you can buy the optional adjustable comb and butt pad package and turn it into a fully-adjustable sniper stock, similar to the Magpul version; check Amazon or elsewhere I've read reviews claiming the LUTH-AR adjustable parts aren't as solid as the Magpul, but once you tighten the bolts down, it's rock-solid...and only $60 vice $280, but to each their own. I've got Magpul stocks, including a higher end stock. Love them, but don't find the LUTH-AR lacking in any way, FWIW.I haven't fired this set up outside of some dry firing. I am including also a brand new Palmetto State bolt carrier group that I had purchased for a different build (will need the packing grease cleaned up). The BCG I had set up in it (used to dry fire practice with) was one I'd used briefly in a Blackout and want to give you everything brand new.I can replace the red highlights with black ones if you prefer for no cost. I have an oversized black trigger guard (not Seeking, but solid) and have an extra black mag release button and a brand new black Strike extended latch charging handle.ADD ONS: If you want additional add-ons, I have these for sale and would be happy to replace the parts on the current set up before selling you the rifle (please email if you want picss:-- Rock River Arms 2 stage trigger $125. I have an extra two stage if you prefer it. For just the cost of the trigger I'll install it for ya.-- Sniper grip. Nice, ergonomic, overmolded grip with a palmswell and hand shelf. Not Ergo brand, but similar to their design and quality (I have both, and this is just as good, just a little less refined). Ergo costs $70, but I'll replace the current grip with this for $30-- Custom "Breacher" stainless single chamber muzzle brake. True muzzle brake, though looks like it might be designed to hide flash as well. This cost $65, but I'll swap it out for the birdcage for $35.-- Rear extended take down pin. I am happy to sell you the pin for $5. If you want me to install it, $15. The rear pin is a hassle to install, or I'd have done it myself already. I bought a rear pin to.match the front pin, but didn't get around to disassembling the buffer tube assembly just to put this in. I was saving to use on a future build.-- Ambidextrous safety, $30. Palmetto State Armory safety, that ran me $20+ shipping. It's a pain to install, since I need to take out the trigger assembly it get the safety to drop out.-- AR soft case for $25.Willing to ship to your FFL (cost of postage) if you prefer--your dealer must accept shipment from a private individual If not, it's $30 + shipping  to send from  my FFL. Otherwise, face to face with VA residents. Must be over 21 and willing to provide copy of VA driver's license (or military ID) and preferably also your CC permit. Cash only (in person) or PMO (for shipping).
